0	User: learn this project, I already did step one, I need to do Part 2.1 exactly, help me do this
1	Assistant:  The user wants help implementing Part 2.1: Ctrl-C signal handling for their shell project. Let me explain what needs to be done clearly.
2	
3	Part 2.1 requires:
4	1. When Ctrl-C is typed while a command is running → the SIGINT is sent to the running command (kills it), not the shell
5	2. When Ctrl-C is typed when no command is running → discard current prompt and print a fresh prompt
6	3. Currently the shell exits when Ctrl-C is typed with no command running
7	
8	Key steps:
9	1. Use `sigaction()` to set up a SIGINT handler in the shell
10	
11	
12	2. The shell needs to catch SIGINT and reprint the prompt, while child processes should have the default signal behavior so they can be terminated by Ctrl-C
13	3. In the signal handler, I'll print a newline and redisplay the prompt, and before forking child processes, I'll reset SIGINT back to its default disposition so they respond normally to Ctrl-C.
14	
15	The handout mentions looking at `ctrl-c.cc` as a reference for handling SIGINT, so I'll use `sigaction` during shell initialization to set up the handler, making sure child processes reset the signal handler after forking.## Part 2.1: Ctrl-C Signal Handling
16	
17	Here's exactly what needs to happen and how to implement it:
18	
19	**Goal:**
20	- Ctrl-C while a command runs → kills the child (not the shell)
21	- Ctrl-C with no command running → discard current line, reprint a fresh prompt
22	- Currently: shell exits entirely on Ctrl-C → fix this
23	
24	---
25	
26	### How it works conceptually
27	
28	When you press Ctrl-C, the terminal sends `SIGINT` to the **foreground process group**. By default, your shell dies too. The fix is:
29	
30	1. Shell **installs a custom SIGINT handler** that just reprints the prompt
31	2. Each **child process resets SIGINT to default** (so it actually gets killed)
32	
33	---
34	
35	### Step 1 — Add the signal handler
36	
37	In `shell.y` or wherever your shell initializes (typically near the top of the `main()` function or the prompt loop), add:
38	
39	```cpp
40	#include <signal.h>
41	
42	// Handler: called in the shell when Ctrl-C is pressed with no chi
43	User: heres shell.y
44	
45	
46	/*
47	 * CS-252
48	 * shell.y: parser for shell
49	 *
50	 * This parser compiles the following grammar:
51	 *
52	 *	cmd [arg]* [> filename]
53	 *
54	 * you must extend it to understand the complete shell grammar
55	 *
56	 */
57	%code requires
58	{
59	#include <string>
60	#if __cplusplus > 199711L
61	#define register      // Deprecated in C++11 so remove the keyword
62	#endif
63	}
64	%union
65	{
66	  char        *string_val;
67	  // Example of using a c++ type in yacc
68	  std::string *cpp_string;
69	}
70	%token <cpp_string> WORD
71	%token NOTOKEN GREAT NEWLINE PIPE LESS GREAT2 GREATAMP GREATGREAT GREATGREATAMP AMP
72	%{
73	//#define yylex yylex
74	#include <cstdio>
75	#include "shell.hh"
76	bool appendMode = false;
77	void yyerror(const char * s);
78	int yylex();
79	%}
80	%%
81	goal:
82	  commands
83	  ;
84	commands:
85	  command
86	  | commands command
87	  ;
88	command: simple_command
89	       ;
90	simple_command:
91	  command_and_args iomodifier_list NEWLINE {
92	    //printf("   Yacc: Execute command\n");
93	    Shell::_currentCommand.execute();
94	  }
95	  | command_and_args iomodifier_list AMP NEWLINE {
96	    //printf("   Yacc: Execute background command\n");
97	    Shell::_currentCommand._background = true;
98	    Shell::_currentCommand.execute();
99	  }
100	  | NEWLINE
101	  | error NEWLINE { yyerrok; }
102	  ;
103	command_and_args:
104	  command_word argument_list {
105	    Shell::_currentCommand.
106	    insertSimpleCommand( Command::_currentSimpleCommand );
107	  }
108	  | command_and_args PIPE command_word argument_list {
109	    Shell::_currentCommand.
110	    insertSimpleCommand( Command::_currentSimpleCommand );
111	  }
112	  ;
113	argument_list:
114	  argument_list argument
115	  | /* can be empty */
116	  ;
117	argument:
118	  WORD {
119	   // printf("   Yacc: insert argument \"%s\"\n", $1->c_str());
120	    Command::_currentSimpleCommand->insertArgument( $1 );\
121	  }
122	  ;
123	command_word:
124	  WORD {
125	    //printf("   Yacc: insert command \"%s\"\n", $1->c_str());
126	    Command::_currentSimpleCommand = new SimpleCommand();
127	    Command::_currentSimpleCommand->insertArgument( $1 );
128	  }
129	  ;
130	iomodifier_list:
131	  iomodifier_list iomodifier
